author: @mikeroitman1830
text: Hi SentDex- New account but long-time subscriber. Thanks for getting content out on such a consistent basis! I imagine that's quite hard, but it's really appreciated by your audience!  What do you think of Rust? Given your basis of curiosity around C/C++, are there any newer languages that offer a 'systems programming' platform that interest you? I've taken to using Rust Lang, but I know that others like Google's Go Lang are catching on throughout the programming world.  Also, I'd guess you get a lot of questions on web programming, as that's in high demand. How much of 'Cloud Computing' do you think is an extension of the web? From the standpoint of someone who's interesting in programming lot's of low-level projects in a system's environment, do you think that cloud computing might offer more work along those lines (as opposed to the feel of a dynamic environment like JS)? What sort's of services do you think will be demanded in the form of small contract work for cloud computing? Maybe a starting point to answering that last question is to ask how broad the scope of cloud computing is? Does it create demand for 1-man-team consultants, all the way up to companies like Amazon and Google? Or is most of the demand localized around big companies (i.e. AWS).  Thanks for your time! I really enjoy your tutorials, as well as your Q&A.

author: @bashisobsolete.pythonismyn6321
text: +sentdex      to make a good video, you MUST record short clips and cut them together.  it sounds like you need to simplify the workflow: > record to a media box (HDMI out) > cut into short clips using cli tools (so much easier than GUI) > soundtrack tweaked in audacity (all clips batch processed, possibly saved in a different format) > sony vegas for the final merge and finishing touches.   PS. fix your lighting !!!  fancy shmancy sony vegas can't fix that.

author: @danweecc
text: I have a question - what if I want to train the network based on two sets of data. For example, I want the network to predict the humidity based on past humidity trends AND past temperature trends. In this case, how should I organize the input layer? I would think that for just one time-series, I would use a regular sliding window on the series. With two series, do I just present both windows (from the humidity and temperature series) to the input layer that is twice the size of the window? if not, how else can I configure the input layer so that it doesn't confuse between the two sets of training data?
